{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486613"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"144"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582438"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:42:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:42:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"144"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/144"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.08,0.05,0.22,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108680"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/144"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"144"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91049"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"737"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5901"},{"type":"tags","id":"8851"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108680"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a recent conscious collapse. He reports onset of double vision followed by his legs suddenly \u0022giving way\u0022 when he was walking from the kitchen to the bedroom. For the past three days he has experienced a tingling sensation in his feet. He was unwell with a viral upper respiratory tract infection two weeks ago, from which he has fully recovered. At that time, he experienced several days of nausea and vomiting, sore throat, and nasal discharge, but no diarrhoea. He has a medical history of type 1 diabetes mellitus with gastroparesis. His regular medications include insulin and metoclopramide. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is bilateral facial weakness with loss of nasolabial folds and inability to lift his eyebrows. There is patchy numbness in both lower limbs to the level of the knees. His reflexes are absent at the knees and ankles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Cerebrovascular event","Diabetic polyneuropathy","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome","Motor neurone disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described is very suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (GBS), characterised by bilateral symmetrical progressive ascending limb weakness, sensory loss and areflexia in the weak limbs, on the background of a recent infection. Cranial nerve palsies are also common, with facial nerve palsies accounting for about half of cases and typically presenting bilaterally. GBS is usually preceded by some form of infection or another immune stimulus that sets off an abnormal autoimmune response. This response usually focuses on peripheral nerves and the associated spinal roots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with a variety of neurological symptoms, but the acute onset, ascending pattern, and bilateral facial nerve involvement are more consistent with GBS. Multiple sclerosis typically causes asymmetrical neurological deficits with a relapsing-remitting pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebrovascular event\u003C/strong\u003E would typically cause unilateral neurological deficits rather than the bilateral, symmetrical ascending weakness seen here. The absence of typical stroke risk factors in this young patient and the pattern of symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic polyneuropathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration given this patient\u0027s diabetes, but it typically develops gradually over years and presents with distal sensory symptoms in a stocking-glove distribution. The acute onset, ascending weakness, and cranial nerve involvement seen here are not typical of diabetic polyneuropathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor neurone disease\u003C/strong\u003E has a more insidious onset over months to years, typically presenting with progressive muscle weakness and wasting without sensory involvement. The acute presentation and sensory symptoms in this case are not consistent with motor neurone disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESome cases of GBS are associated with a preceding diarrhoeal illness, where \u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/em\u003E infection appears to be a significant trigger. However, this patient did not have diarrhoea with his recent viral illness. A lumbar puncture may reveal albuminocytologic dissociation, with elevated protein but normal cell count. Nerve conduction studies may be helpful in classifying the variant of GBS, but are not necessary for diagnosis. The duration of the illness is usually less than four weeks, with symptoms usually being maximal within two weeks of onset. Up to 30% of patients will develop respiratory complications and some may need ventilatory support in an intensive care unit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome typically presents with acute progressive ascending weakness, areflexia, and sensory symptoms following a recent infection.","Facial nerve palsy in Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome is usually bilateral, occurring in approximately 50% of cases.","Respiratory muscle involvement occurs in up to 30% of patients with Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome, requiring close monitoring and potential ventilatory support."],"references":["Nguyen TP, Taylor RS. Guillain-Barre Syndrome. 2023 Feb 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30335287.","Willison HJ, Jacobs BC, van Doorn PA. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome. Lancet. 2016 Aug 13;388(10045):717-27. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00339-1. Epub 2016 Mar 2. PMID: 26948435.","Bellanti R, Rinaldi S. Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome: a comprehensive review. Eur J Neurol. 2024 Aug;31(8):e16365. doi: 10.1111/ene.16365. Epub 2024 May 30. PMID: 38813755; PMCID: PMC11235944."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91049"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"144"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91049"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-12T18:56:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T18:58:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"it